content.text: We can help you manage your weight without sacrificing the things you love. Making simple changes in how you approach nutrition and physical activity can help you improve your overall health. By mastering skills using achievable action steps, you can work towards meeting your goals. First, we need to see if this program is a good fit for you.

Balance is NOT intended for 
  • pregnant women,
  • anyone who has or suspects they have an eating disorder,
  • anyone who is physically or medically unable to exercise, or 
  • anyone who is unable to walk for exercise. 

If you fall into any of these four categories, you should not participate in this program. Please contact your health care provider to discuss weight management. 

Do any of the four listed categories apply to you?

Are any of the following statements true for you?
  • Your doctor has said that you have a heart condition, and you should only do physical activity recommended by a doctor.
  • You feel pain in your chest when you do physical activity.
  • In the past month, you had chest pain when you weren't doing physical activity.
  • You get dizzy and lose your balance, or lose consciousness.
  • You have a bone or joint problem (back, knee, or hip, for example) that could be made worse by a change in your physical activity.
  • Your doctor is currently prescribing drugs (for example, water pills) for your blood pressure or heart condition.
  • There is any other reason why you should not do physical activity.

content.text: There are many reasons why you may want to manage your weight. We know it can be hard to choose just one, but which of the following is most important to you?
Great. We'll help you achieve your goal. After all, your goals are our goals. Now, let's move from the “why” to the “what.”

choice.text: I want to maintain my current weight.
I want to lose more than 30 pounds.

You’re looking to lose weight because you’d like to live life to the fullest. Your quality of life isn't great and your current weight may lead to some health problems. We're here to support you in improving your health and quality of life.

content.text: You may already know that successful weight management is a combination of healthy eating and being active (the old "calories in, calories out" equation). We'd like to know what you want to focus on first to help you reach your goals.

choice.text: Getting motivated: I’m just not that excited about eating healthy.
Staying motivated: I start out doing well, but I seem to lose interest over time.
Eating the right types of foods: I’m not sure what I should eat.
Eating the right amount of foods: I tend to eat portions that are too big, or don’t know how much to eat.
Resisting temptations: There are a lot of things around me that make it easy to eat unhealthy.
Having a better mindset about food: I turn to food for comfort, use it as a reward, or feel guilty about eating.
I don't have any trouble eating healthy.

Okay. Ready to really dive in? The more you tell us, the more we can help you develop skills to meet your goals. Let’s get to it.

You want to work on getting active and sticking with changes to your eating habits, but there are some things standing in your way. Let’s take a deeper look into that so we can choose the right skills for you.
First of all, how motivated are you to manage your weight?

content.text: We’d like to know a little more about what’s behind your motivation. Think about the following statements and let us know how much they sound like you.
How confident are you that you can manage your weight?

Motivation and confidence are both important when it comes to managing your weight. With each small success you gain, your motivation and confidence are likely to grow, and you'll get closer to your overall goal.

choice.text: ACCOMPLISHMENT - mastery of knowledge, skills, abilities
ADVENTURE - seeking big rewards from big risks
BALANCE - inner peace, centered, moderate, perspective
COMMUNITY - participating in groups that share your neighborhood, type of work, or beliefs
COURAGE - testing limits, facing difficulties with resilience
CREATIVITY - imagination, new ways of doing and seeing
FUN - enjoyment, playfulness, sense of play
GENEROSITY - sharing time, money, and energy with others
GROWTH - forward motion in personal development
INTEGRITY - honesty, strength of character, and justice in dealings with others
RELATIONSHIPS - strong, active bonds with family and friends
RESPECT - fair treatment, valuing individuals for uniqueness
SPIRITUALITY - connection with something larger than the "here and now"
SERVICE - to be of assistance and support to a person or cause

content.text: We'd like to ask you about something that might surprise you – what drives you? It's important to tie changes in your life to the things that are most important to you. So what do you consider to be your "core values?" Please choose the three that mean the most to you and that define you as a person.
Based on what you’ve shared, we have some great ideas on how to help boost your motivation as you work on managing your weight. You’ll find these in your Building Motivation skill.
You’re looking to drop more than 10 pounds. An active lifestyle will be a key part to your success in reaching your goal and keeping the weight off long term.

choice.text: I sit or stand most of the day.
I sit or stand part of the day, but am moving around for part of the day as well.

content.text: Which of the following best describes your typical day?

During moderate-intensity activities, you’re able to hold a conversation, but you’re working hard enough to raise your heart rate and break a sweat. Brisk walking, casual swimming and doubles tennis are examples of moderate-intensity activities.
In a typical week, what is the average amount of time you spend doing moderate-intensity physical activity?

During vigorous-intensity activities, you’re breathing hard and fast, and your heart rate has gone up quite a bit. If you’re working at this level, you won’t be able to say more than a few words without pausing for a breath. These types of activities include running, bicycling, swimming laps, and weight circuit training.
In a typical week, what is the average amount of time you spend doing vigorous-intensity physical activity?
How about strength-training exercises, such as using free weights, weight machines, or resistance bands? How often do you do those?

Current physical activity guidelines call for 150 minutes of moderate activity plus 2 days of strength training a week. Sound overwhelming? Don’t worry. In your Being Active skill, we’re going to help you find ways to bump up your activity level from what you’re currently doing today.
We know you’re ready to focus on making some changes to your eating habits. We'd like to know more about what – and how – you currently eat.

choice.text: Anything with cheese front and center

Thanks for filling us in. This gives us a good base to figure out what will be the most helpful as you work on developing your Eating Well and Managing Portion Size skills.
Our minds can be our own worst enemy. We have a couple of questions to help us understand how you think, so that we can help you get past any thoughts that might be getting in the way of your goals.

choice.text: "I'm so overwhelmed. I can't do anything right."
I have negative thoughts that are different than the ones listed above.

content.text: How do you feel about your body?

content.text: This next question may seem like it’s coming from left field, but it will help us understand how focused you are. Which of the following statements describe your experiences over the past week?
Great. Your answers will help us refine your skills on Being Mindful, Accepting Your Body, and Reshaping Your Thoughts. These can help you get your mind in a good place to get to work on your goals.
For many people, stress can undermine both their efforts at healthy eating and their exercise routine. We just have a few more questions for you about stress, energy, and sleep.
How much energy do you feel you've had over the past week?
Over the past week, how much sleep did you generally get in each 24-hour period?

content.helpText: Choose a lower number if you haven’t been sleeping well. Choose a higher number if you have been sleeping well.
content.text: How would you rate the overall quality of your sleep?
In the past month, how often have you felt nervous and stressed?

We know stress is a normal part of life and we want you to be able to manage it if you start to feel the pressure. Your Learning to Relax skill will give you some great strategies to help you manage any stress you may be feeling. The better you can manage stress, the less likely it will be to derail your weight management efforts.

Whether you have one person who is your rock, or a number of people who you turn to for different types of support, a support system is important when you’re making big changes. Let’s learn a little more about yours.

content.text: How do the people around you affect your health habits?

Having people in your corner can make managing your weight a little easier. You also live in a world where social events are based around eating. We’ll help you to make the most of your support system as well as give you some ideas about navigating the social side of being healthy.
Alright, we have a few more questions that will help us figure out how much your health is impacting your day-to-day life.
Are you currently employed (working for pay)?

We’re going to ask you to think about how your health problems affect your ability to do your regular daily activities. By regular activities, we mean the usual things you do day-to-day, such as work around the house, shopping, child care, exercising, studying, etc. Think about times you were limited in the amount or kind of activities you could do, and times you accomplished less than you would like because of your health. If health problems affected your activities only a little or not at all, choose a low number. Choose a high number if health problems affected your activities a great deal.

Health problems completely prevented me from doing my daily activities
